- VSCode Version: 1.0.0-insider
- OS Version: Windows 10

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Open any js file with abundant variables and functions
2. Compare with any other popular editor e.g. sublime, atom, brackets, etc

VS Code is a fantastic editor. However, for an editor that accentuates support for JavaScript, the syntax highlighting is less than sub-par. 

To illustrate, here's VS Code and Sublime using the same color scheme:
![vsc_](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/11352152/14573672/6ef0d336-0324-11e6-8b8a-6953b87cb469.PNG)
![subl3](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/11352152/14573673/6ef1c106-0324-11e6-8a62-d2f3fdc460f4.PNG)

The color scheme isn't at fault since the default (dark+) theme is not much better
![vsc](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/11352152/14573691/88886d72-0324-11e6-9eaa-23a3acde6431.PNG)

Here's the code in screenshot:

``` javascript
init = function () {

        navigationCurrentMonth.className = 'flatpickr-current-month';
        calendarContainer.className = 'flatpickr-calendar';
        calendar.className = "flatpickr-days";

        instanceConfig = instanceConfig || {};

        self.config = {};
        self.element = element;

        for (var config in self.defaultConfig)
            self.config[config] =
                instanceConfig[config] ||
                self.element.dataset&&self.element.dataset[config.toLowerCase()] ||
                self.element.getAttribute("data-"+config)||
                self.defaultConfig[config];


        self.input = (self.config.wrap) ? element.querySelector("[data-input]") : element;    

        if(self.config.defaultDate){
            self.config.defaultDate = uDate(self.config.defaultDate);
        }

        if ( self.input.value || self.config.defaultDate )
            self.selectedDateObj = uDate(self.config.defaultDate||self.input.value);

       self.config.minDate =
            uDate(self.config.minDate === "today" ? new Date() : self.config.minDate, true);

       self.config.maxDate = uDate(self.config.maxDate, true);

        self.jumpToDate(self.selectedDateObj||self.config.minDate||currentDate);

        wrap();        
        buildCalendar();
        bind();

        if (!self.config.noCalendar)
            updateValue();
    };
```

Significant and _absolutely necessary_ enhancements can be brought in by highlighting:
- Variables
- Function names
- Methods

- VSCode Version: 1.0.0
- OS Version: Windows 7 SP1

In a vary simple project that consists of two files 

```
-- apiService.js
-- index.js
```

The apiService code looks like: 

```
var axios = require('axios');
//import axios from 'axios';

const service = {
    /**
     * Triggers a get http request
     * @param {string} url - The url of the request
     */
    get(url) {
        return axios.get(url);
    }
};

export default service;
```

When requiring the axios library in this way there is intellisense provided by typings which I have install for axios libary as seen in the following picture
![valid](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/487416/14562123/3420ed80-031b-11e6-8e72-2fc64fd71463.png)

If we use the ES6 way of importing the library (swap the commenting if first two lines) then the intellisense is gone.

What I noticed though is that this import syntax works perfectly fine when importing my modules as indicating here
![index](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/487416/14562221/bbadaf72-031b-11e6-8018-f44f87cbdf98.png)

My jsconfig file looks like 

```
{
    "compilerOptions": {
        "module": "es6"
    },
    "exclude": [
        "node_modules"
    ]
}
```

And I tried the other available options for module.

- VSCode Version: 1.0
- OS Version: Windows 7

Steps to Reproduce:
1.  Create new directory with .vscode/settings.json
2. Add json schema for swagger 2.0 to the settings.json: 

   ```
   // Place your settings in this file to overwrite default and user settings.
   {
    "json.schemas": [
      {
        "fileMatch": [
          "*.json"
        ],
        "url": "http://json.schemastore.org/swagger-2.0"
      }
    ]
   }
   ```
3. Create new json file and see that autocomplete according to the swagger 2.0 json schema isn't working.

